ip, and Civic Engagement -- t11 Rungh: The Many Colours of a Pan-Ethnoracial Medium -- t12. Anti-Racist and Feminist Organizing in Canada’s Media Industries: A Closer Look at Didihood: The Sisterhood of South Asian Creatives in Canada -- t13. Constructing Crime in Canadian Ethnic Minority Media: A Qualitative Study of South Asian and Black Newspapers -- t14. The Ideology of Hindutva in the Canadian Hindu Diaspora’s Media: A Critical Examination of the Integrative and Non-Integrative Discourses -- t15. Innovative Models in Ethnic Media 2.0: A Practitioner’s Reflections -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEthnic minority groups in Canada have set up their own communication infrastructure that has evolved over time from the analog to the digital age, and continues to remain relevant across generations. Offering a reassessment of contemporary media outlets, The Handbook of Ethnic Media in Canada asks how ethnic media have changed, why they continue to be relevant, and what impact this media sector has on ethnocultural communities as well as broader society.Building on past studies that highlight particular functions of ethnic media – publishing information that is vital to settlement and civic engagement and providing an alternative to mainstream media, among others – this volume generates insights on new dynamics of the ethnic media sector that are prevalent in the digital age. Contributors re-examine theoretical and methodological approaches to ethnic media research, explore the practices of ethnic media along cultural, linguistic, and religious lines, and interrogate the policies that affect ethnic media production and consumption. At its core, the question of how Canadians engage with ethnic media is a question about what this media sector means for the sociocultural, economic, and political integration of Canadians, both majority and minority, and Canada’s race relations.The Handbook of Ethnic Media in Canada provides a rich resource for anyone concerned about the role media plays in the complex relationship between ethnicity, race, belonging, and marginality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aadvertising.  aantiracist.  abroadcasting.  acommunication infrastructure.  afeminist.  aintegration.  ajournalism.  amulticulturalism.  aproduction.  arace relations.  arepresentation.1 aAhadi, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAhadi, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAl-Rawi, Ahmed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl-Rawi, Ahmed, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBains, Alysha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernard-Brind’Amour, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakraborty, Indranil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDatta, Anisha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouai, Aziz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleras, Augie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayward, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJiwani, Yasmin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarim, Karim H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiftari, Naser, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Paul S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNayab Bukhari, Syeda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNg, Elim, 